The City Commission received the following e-mail message from a citizen:

From: E K Sommer [mailto:eksommer@bellsouth.net] 
Sent: Tuesday, July 04, 2017 2:11 PM
To: citycomm
Cc: markhelms@ufl.edu
Subject: Trash along State Road 24

I would like to bring to the attention of the Gainesville City Commissioners, the trash that often accumulates along the south side of State Road 24 between UF Health Shands and the Malcom Randall VA Hospital.

I gather that this area is sort of a “no-man’s” land with jurisdiction shared (or not shared) between the City, the University of Florida/Shands, and the VA.

I often walk from the parking garage near the corner of Gale Lemerand Dr and State Road 24 to my office in the Shands Facilities Administration Building. I am dismayed at the trash along the walking area—especially the medical related trash such as latex gloves and face masks and sadly copious cigarette butts.

Mostly recently it has been less littered, and I did make mention of the problem to someone at Shands—so perhaps some action was taken.

But what I would hope in the long term is that the entities involved would work together to provide regular clean up this area and a cooperative educational program for visitors, patients, and employees.

Because of the prominence of the UF Health Shands medical facility and the regional status of the VA, we have a lot of people from out of town visiting this area, and I would hope that the city, the hospitals, and the local community would take pride in showing visitors a well-kept public corridor.

Thank you.

Eleanor K. Sommer, M.Sc.
Graduate Programs Advisor & Adjunct Lecturer
Center for Arts in Medicine
University of Florida College of the Arts
PO Box 100141
Gainesville FL 32610
http://artsinmedicine.arts.ufl.edu/arts-in-medicine-programs 
352-594-4564
location_detail: SSIDE OF SR24 BETWEEN UF HEALTH & VA HOSPITAL

description:
Commissioner Arreola received the following e-mail from Deb Lancaster on 7/19, 7am:

Good morning.  I called yesterday afternoon and spoke with a customer service rep who advised she would transfer me to your extension.  Instead, I was sent to the voice mailbox of Adrian Santos-Hayes.  I left a message, requesting that he transfer my message to you.  In case that does not occur, I am emailing my request to you.

I reside at 4201 NW 14th PL.  I am a 64 year old widow who somehow manages to keep her yard in decent shape, which activities include mowing.  So, how it is that the City of Gainesville, with its vast resources cannot mow the grass circle on our street?  I have lived there for 41 years and the circle has been mowed regularly (every month or so) each summer.  I'm not normally a complainer, but the height of the grass/weeks is absurd.  I am 5 ft 6 and the weeds come up to my shoulder in some spots.  Of course when I checked that out, I had to wear hard, enclosed shoes, for fear of snakebite. And who knows what other wildlife is lurking amongst the overgrowth? The neighborhood kids, who sometimes use that circle for touch football or other activities, are unable to use it due to the jungle-like conditions.  If the City waits much longer, it's going to need a bush-hog.  By the way, I have observed the mowing many times in the past.  It typically takes no longer than 15-20 minutes to accomplish.  Of course, in its current state, it may now take much longer to mow.

Kindly forward my request to the appropriate department.  FYI, I have made two telephone calls to Public Works in the last few weeks, and have been told "it's on schedule" to be mowed.

Thank you for your consideration and assistance.

Deb Lancaster

-----Original Message-----
From: Alix Baxter [mailto:alixbaxter47@gmail.com] 
Sent: Wednesday, October 20, 2021 11:01 AM
To: Poe, Lauren B 
Cc: Arreola, David I ; Saco, Reina E ; Ward, Harvey L ; Hayes-Santos, Adrian ; Walker, Desmon N 
Subject: Mixed use development at 43rd St and 23rd Ave

Mayor Poe and the Gainesville City Commission - I’m not sure I have ever written to a local politician before - usually state or federal office holders, but I feel compelled to write after reading the Mayor’s comments in today’s paper about high density development leading to less traffic and how the 225 apartments or units will be lived in likely by people without cars. Thus, in your mind, another reason traffic will not get worse at that intersection - 43rd  St and 23rd Ave. I’m sorry - but aren’t you part of the same commission trying to cut down on student deaths on University Ave - near 13th - not exactly a low density area - and aren’t you getting ready to spend money to re-do that section of the road - 13th and University Ave to improve traffic flow and make it safer? And downtown - on Main Street - again not exactly a low density area and traffic moves at a crawl - one lane each way - but no lessening of traffic. Who ever gave you the info that high density areas have less traffic? The source  obviously has a study that shows that, but my experience in medicine has proven that one can cite a study that supports just about anything one believes in or wants to do. Data needs to be analyzed carefully. 

And as for the mayor’s  comment about people living in apartments  there not having cars - well, not having a car is workable if work is nearby or if bus service takes you near your work place - but usually if it is an apartment - with more than one occupant - at least one person is likely to own a car which will transport not just themselves but others as well. I don’t know if you have noticed very many bicyclists heading off to work on Gainesville streets - a few east of Waldo Road and of course UF Students. Putting 220

Re:  Traffic Impact of Proposed Royal Park Apartment complex on existing Woodland Terrace residential neighborhood

Hello:

I am not sure to whom I should direct this question/concern, so will ask our Gainesville City Commission for direction.

As Background:
I am a long-time home-owner in the Woodland Terrace neighborhood in Gainesville, Florida - an old established subdivision of small, single family homes off University Avenue.  It is our understanding that a large, multi-family apartment complex (192 units), to be known as Royal Park Apartments, is planned for development on currently landlocked acreage behind the Royal Park movie theater and adjacent to the Woodland Terrace and Golf Club Manor Subdivisions (a misnomer, since there is no Golf Club anywhere nearby!).  

I could not find much local information regarding the proposed project, so I am not certain of the actual development plan.  However, I did find some information on the internet regarding the issuance of tax exempt bonds to finance the project, which indicates a desire to develop the acreage, See:  

 - https://floridahousing.org/docs/default-source/data-docs-and-reports/boardpackages/2021/july-30/consent-items/MMRB_Ex_G.pdf 
 - https://floridahousing.org/docs/default-source/aboutflorida/notice-of-public-hearing/notice-of-public-hearing---royal-park.pdf?sfvrsn=95adf77b_2

It is our understanding that there is some difficulty in accessing this acreage and various proposals are under consideration regarding future traffic flow - and that one proposed route may be via an access road to be built at the meeting point of NW 5th Ave. and NW 36th Dr., on a small lot located between two existing houses. See:
- https://qpublic.schneidercorp.com/Application.aspx?AppID=1081&LayerID=26490&PageTypeID=1&PageID=10767&Q=1955578386&KeyValue=06496-000-000

This possible route to the Royal Park Apartment complex would significantly increase the traffic flow on NW 5th Ave, and could turn what is now a relatively quiet, speed-bumped neighborhood road, into a heavily

The issue is the renters of this property keep construction equipment parts, more specifically, a front end loader bucket on the South side of their house (Facing NW 43 Pl). This bucket has been sitting on the side of their house for months. Please have them remove this bucket. Since this bucket has been sitting here since at least February, one can reasonably assume that it has been abandoned and since it goes to a motorized piece of equipment, one can assume it falls into the Section 13-171 of City of Gainesville Code of Ordinances  and can reasonably be considered a part of a vehicle, therefore in violation of Section 13-171(b), which states:  It shall be unlawful for the owner or occupant of a residential building structure or property to utilize the premises of the residential property for the open outdoor storage of any blight-inducing materials such as abandoned motor vehicle or part thereof including tires, icebox, refrigerator, stove, or other appliances, planks, timbers, glass, or other building material, building rubbish, packing material, barrels, bottles, cans, boxes or similar items. Failure to comply with this subsection shall be a major violation.

To whom it may concern, 

Hello. I am currently a resident living in a tent at Dignity Village, and I would like to make a request concerning a recent change in waste management. 

My tent is located in the first section of the southwest corner at Grace Marketplace. There is a road that circles around Grace, and as you are heading south on the road, just before you turn the corner to go east, there is a designated area at the edge of the lot, which contains 3 porta-potties and a cube shaped dumpster with two lids. Both the porta-potties and the dumpster are situated a minimum of 50-60 ft away from any tents. Or, you might say - none of the residents have chosen to set up their tents within 50-60 ft of the designated bathroom and dumpster area. This seems to be a sufficient distance for everyone. However, on Friday morning, January 31st, the dumpster was removed, and a large rectangular dumpster with no lids was placed right in the middle of the main tent area, within 15-20 ft of several of the tents, including my own. 

Although I do not contribute to this myself, it is an unfortunate truth of this type of living environment that the dumpsters will tend to contain urine, feces, and other raw waste, such as old meat. Because of its close vicinity, and because it does not have any lids, I am able to smell the waste from my tent, and there are flies whenever I walk outside my door.

In addition to this, it causes an excess of noise, which has made it difficult for me to sleep at night. When the dumpster is moved from 60 ft away (where it was) to 15ft away (where it is now), it may appear to be a subtle difference to an outsider, but it causes a sound increase of 12db, which more than doubles the perceived volume. Whenever anything is thrown into the dumpster, it usually creates a loud thud sound, which I can not only hear, but I can feel as well, as it shakes the ground. 

I do understand that living in a tent, I am not in a position to expect the same standards as someone living in a house or an apartment, but I would like to respectfully request that the dumpster be moved to its previous position, or to another suitable position that would be located 50 or more feet from any of the tents. And preferably I believe it ought to be the kind of dumpster with lids, so that the flies and smell may be better contained. 

In regards to sound, I do not expect total quiet, and accordingly, I wear earphones literally 24hrs/day. Under normal conditions, the headphones are sufficient for blocking all or most of the sound from the surrounding area. But with the dumpster in its new location, I am able to hear trash being thrown several times per hour, and as I said, this occurs after 10pm at night as well.

Another problem is that the dumpster tends to create debris, and attract scavengers. For example, currently there is a heap of scrap tent materials between the dumpster and my tent. The accepted etiquette here is for anything which may potentially be of use to be left outside the dumpster. Additionally, there are people who regularly check the dumpster for these types of things, and there are also people who regularly go into the dumpster itself in order to retrieve aluminum cans and other items. 

Since the dumpster has been placed in its current position, it has been extremely disturbing for me. If it is possible to move the dumpster to where it was previously, and to return to the type with lids, I would be very grateful for your concern. 

Thank you. 

David Cole Arnold

David.Cole.Arnold@Gmail.com
(352)871-2441

Not really about overgrown, this is about the lost opportunity to beautify our traffic circles WITHOUT blocking the views of what's behind them. Two ways, blocking either the architecture or the street behind. Shown is just one example of trying to fill a circle, but (if successful) would block the view to the Cade Museum — not very tourist friendly to do that. Some palms died, but a live oak was added right in the viewline, too. Instead of filling every circle with plant life, which blends in with backgrounds in other locations, please consider architectural shapes like obelisks, arches, columns, lighthouses, sculptures, etc to show drivers they need to slow down. Well lit at night as well. I think filling circles with only trees and bushes blends in with backgrounds sometimes, and new residents or tourists won't slow down in time. Since this is a new and cost related idea, perhaps local arts patrons or nearby businesses could sponsor the non-plant roundabout markers?
